{"id": 225045522, "title": "Navigating Tax Controversies: Resolving Disputes With The IRS", "text": "Share to Facebook Share to Twitter Share to Linkedin Cofounder of Victory Tax Law | Tax Lawyer. getty Tax controversies with the IRS can be complex and challenging for taxpayers. However, with the right strategies and guidance, these disputes can be effectively resolved. As a tax attorney with many years of experience in handling such cases, I fundamentally understand the importance of a strategic approach at any stage of the dispute. I'm hoping to share insights that can help you develop a firm grasp on the essentials and bring forth strategies that can serve you in better navigating tax controversies and achieving a favorable resolution. Understanding The IRS Perspective To effectively navigate a tax controversy with the IRS, it's crucial to understand their perspective. In essence, the IRS is enforcing tax laws to make sure that taxpayers fulfill their obligations. Naturally, observing the situation from their perspective can help taxpayers navigate disputes more effectively. Effective Communication Is Key Clear and concise communication is essential when dealing with the IRS. It's important to articulate your position clearly while providing all of the relevant information and supporting documentation. Additionally, maintaining a professional and respectful tone in all communications can help facilitate a resolution\u2014as aggression is never the answer. It's important to note that fax is the preferred method for submitting information to the IRS, as they do not typically use email. If you opt to mail something, expect a response within 6-12 weeks. MORE FOR YOU Trump Trial Prosecutor Ends Closing Argument After Nearly 5 Hours\u2014Jury Instructions Set For Wednesday Gas Explosion In Downtown Youngstown, Ohio Injures At Least 7 Trump Lashes Out At Robert De Niro After Actor Calls Him A Tyrant Outside Courthouse Utilizing Available Resources When facing a tax controversy, it's important to leverage available resources to support your case. One of the most reliable options is consulting with tax professionals, such as tax attorneys or accountants, who can provide expert advice and guidance, which can help you obtain a clear picture of the given situation, avoiding panic. In fact, services that advocate for taxpayers can be incredibly helpful in guiding you through each layer of the process, as their purpose is to make sure your rights are protected. Alongside consulting with tax professionals, irs.gov is a valuable resource for managing taxes efficiently. It provides tools and information for tasks like checking refund status, accessing tax records and making payments online. The site also offers free tax filing, forms and instructions, as well as answers to tax questions and the ability to apply for an Employer ID Number (EIN). You can also check the status of your amended return on the site. Tax transcripts are vital for understanding your tax history. As a tax attorney, I often advise clients on their importance, as they contain key details from past tax returns and any IRS adjustments. Understanding how to access and interpret these transcripts is crucial for resolving tax issues or applying for loans. You can access your tax records online or by mail, including past returns, tax account details and income statements. Business tax transcripts require a separate request. Your Online Account offers a quick way to check balances, view payment history and see prior year AGI. Requesting transcripts online is fast; have a photo ID ready. If online isn't an option, you can request by mail, arriving in 5 to 10 days. Another option is to request by calling 1-800-908-9946. Understanding Your Rights And Options Taxpayers have rights when resolving tax disputes with the IRS. Knowing your rights is crucial, as this can empower you to navigate the process confidently and protect your interests. For instance, you have the right to appeal IRS decisions and to be represented by a qualified tax professional. Exploring Settlement Options In many cases, resolving a tax controversy with the IRS involves exploring settlement options. This may include negotiating a settlement agreement, where both parties agree on a resolution that is acceptable to them. Settlement agreements can help you avoid lengthy and costly litigation, making them a valuable option to consider. Seeking Professional Assistance Navigating a tax controversy with the IRS can be complex, and seeking professional assistance is often advisable. Tax professionals, such as tax attorneys or accountants, can effectively lead you through every step of the process, significantly increasing your chances of achieving a favorable resolution. Litigation As A Last Resort While settlement is often the preferred outcome in tax controversies, litigation may be necessary in some cases. If negotiations fail to produce a satisfactory resolution, you may choose to pursue litigation through tax court. Quite surely, it's important to weigh the potential costs and benefits of litigation carefully before proceeding. Additional Strategies For Resolving Tax Controversies In addition to the strategies we've already discussed, there are several other approaches that taxpayers can take to resolve tax controversies with the IRS. These include: \u2022 Offer In Compromise (OIC): An OIC is an agreement between a taxpayer and the IRS that settles the taxpayer's tax liability for less than the full amount owed. To qualify for an OIC, taxpayers must meet specific criteria and demonstrate an inability to pay the full amount of tax owed. \u2022 Installment Agreements: An installment agreement allows taxpayers to pay their tax debt over time in monthly installments. This option can be particularly useful for those, who aren't able to pay their tax debt in full, but do have the means to make monthly payments. \u2022 Collection Due Process (CDP) Hearing: Taxpayers have the right to request a CDP hearing before the IRS initiates certain collection actions, such as a levy or lien. During the hearing, taxpayers can present their case and potentially reach a resolution with the IRS. Navigating tax controversies with the IRS demands a strategic approach and a deep understanding of the process. By grasping the IRS's perspective, communicating effectively, using available resources, knowing your rights, exploring settlements and seeking professional help, you can resolve disputes and achieve a favorable outcome. As a tax attorney, I've seen these strategies work for my clients and hope they'll guide you to a successful resolution. The information provided here is not investment, tax or financial advice. You should consult with a licensed professional for advice concerning your specific situation. Forbes Business Council is the foremost growth and networking organization for business owners and leaders. Do I qualify? Follow me on LinkedIn. Check out my website. Parham Khorsandi Editorial Standards Print Reprints & Permissions", "summary": "Navigating tax controversies with the IRS demands a strategic approach and a deep understanding of the process.", "url": "https://www.forbes.com/sites/forbesbusinesscouncil/2024/05/29/navigating-tax-controversies-resolving-disputes-with-the-irs/", "image": "https://imageio.forbes.com/specials-images/imageserve/663e6cb989693a54ea4bcef3/0x0.jpg?format=jpg&height=900&width=1600&fit=bounds", "video": null, "publish_date": "2024-05-29 14:00:00", "author": "Forbes Councils Member,Parham Khorsandi", "authors": ["Forbes Councils Member", "Parham Khorsandi"], "language": "en", "source_country": "US", "sentiment": 0.709}